\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Sites\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. Represents the physical location (like offices, branches, data centers).\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. A site is defined by one or more IP subnets.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}3. Helps control replication traffic between DCs in different locations.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Subnets\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. Used to map IP addresses to AD sites.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Ensures clients authenticate with the nearest DC to improve performance.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Site Links\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 1. Define the network connection between two or more sites.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Control replication schedule and cost (bandwidth usage).\b\f0\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\f3 7. What is the Logical components of Active Directory?\par
\b0 Ans. Logical Components of AD:\par
\b Forest \b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. The topmost logical container.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. A collection of one or more domain trees that share a common schema, configuration, and global catalog.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Domain\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. A logical group of objects (users, computers, groups) sharing the same namespace (e.g., corp.local).\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Acts as a security boundary for policies and authentication.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Tree\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. A collection of one or more domains in a hierarchical structure.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Domains in a tree share a contiguous namespace (e.g., corp.local, sales.corp.local).\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Organizational Units (OUs)\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 1. Containers within a domain used to group objects (users, computers, groups).\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Allow delegation of administration and application of Group Policies.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Objects\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. The basic elements stored in AD (users, computers, groups, printers, etc.).\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Each object has attributes (like username, password, email).\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Global Catalog \b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 1. A distributed data repository that contains a searchable index of all objects in a forest.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Helps users find resources across domains\b\f0\par

