\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 11. Explain the term forest in AD?\par
\b0 Ans. In Active Directory (AD), a forest is the topmost logical container that holds one or more domain trees which share a common schema, configuration, and global catalog.\par
\b Key Points:\b0\par
1. Highest-level structure in AD hierarchy.\par
\b 2.Domains in a forest can have different namespaces but share:\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 1. Schema\b  \b0 (defines object types & attributes)\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}2. Configuration (replication and topology info)\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}3. Global Catalog (for searching objects across domains)\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 3.Trust relationships:\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 1. Domains within a forest automatically trust each other (two-way transitive trust).\par

