\b 24. Explain the process of creating and managing Group Policy Objects (GPOs) in Windows Server 2016 or 2019?\par
\b0 Ans. What is a GPO?\par
A Group Policy Object (GPO) is a set of rules and configurations applied to users or computers in an Active Directory (AD) environment.\par
Used to enforce security settings, software installations, desktop restrictions, etc.\par
GPOs are linked to sites, domains, or organizational units (OUs).\par
\b Steps to Create and Manage GPOs\b0\par
\b 1. Open Group Policy Management Console (GPMC)\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 Go to Server Manager \f2\u8594?\f0  Tools \f2\u8594?\f0  Group Policy Management.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}The GPMC window opens, showing your forest, domains, and OUs.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 2. Create a New GPO\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj In the left pane, expand your domain.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Right-click Group Policy Objects \f2\u8594?\f0  New.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Enter a name for the GPO (e.g., \f2\ldblquote\f0 Password Policy\f2\rdblquote\f0  or \f2\ldblquote\f0 Desktop Restrictions\f2\rdblquote\f0 ).\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}The new GPO now appears under Group Policy Objects.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 3. Edit the GPO\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj Right-click the GPO \f2\u8594?\f0  Edit.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}The Group Policy Management Editor opens.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Configure settings under:\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Computer Configuration \f2\u8594?\f0  policies for computers (startup scripts, security, updates).\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}User Configuration \f2\u8594?\f0  policies for users (desktop settings, folder redirection, logon scripts).\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 4. Link the GPO\b0\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\lang1033 1. Decide where to apply the GPO:\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj Site\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Domain\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}OU\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\lang1033 2. Right-click the target container (e.g., an OU) \f2\u8594?\f0  Link an Existing GPO.\par
\lang1033 3. Select your GPO \f2\u8594?\f0  OK.\par
\b 5. Apply and Test the GPO\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj Run gpupdate /force on a client to refresh policies.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Verify applied policies using:\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj gpresult /r\par
or\par
Get-GPResultantSetOfPolicy -ReportType Html -Path C:\\GPReport.html\par
\b 6. Manage GPOs\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b Enable/Disable GPO: \b0 Right-click GPO \f2\u8594?\f0  Enable/Disable.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}\b Enforce GPO\b0 : Prevents lower-level GPOs from overriding it.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}\b Block Inheritance: \b0 Stops higher-level GPOs from applying to an OU.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}\b Backup/Restore GPOs: \b0 Right-click GPO \f2\u8594?\f0  Back Up / Import Settings.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}\b Delegate Control: \b0 Assign permissions for who can edit or link GPOs\b .\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 25\f3 . \f0 What\f3  \f0 are\f3  \f0 Organizational\f3  \f0 Units\f3  (\f0 OUs\f3 ) \f0 in\f3  \f0 Active\f3  \f0 Directory\f3 , \f0 and\f3  \f0 how\f3  \f0 do\f3  \f0 you\f3  \f0 use them\f3 ?\par
\b0\f0 Ans. What are Organizational Units (OUs)?\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj An Organizational Unit (OU) is a container object in Active Directory used to organize users, groups, computers, and other OUs within a domain.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Think of it like a folder inside AD that helps manage and apply policies in a structured way.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}OUs do not have separate security boundaries (unlike domains) \u8594? they are mainly for organization and administration.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b How are OUs Used?\par
1. Organizing AD Objects\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 Group related users, computers, or groups in one OU for easy management.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Example: Create OUs like HR, IT, Sales, or Computers.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 2. Delegating Administration\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj You can assign limited permissions to junior admins or department heads only on a specific OU.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Example: HR team can manage accounts only in the HR OU, not the whole domain.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 3. Applying Group Policies (GPOs)\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj GPOs can be linked to OUs to enforce specific rules/settings.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Example: Apply stricter security policies to the Finance OU but not the Sales OU.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 4. Simplifying Management\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 Easier to locate and manage AD objects when structured in OUs.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Supports nesting \u8594? OUs can contain other OUs.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Example: OU = Sales \u8594? Sub-OU = Regional Sales.\b\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj 26. Describe the process of delegating administrative privileges in Active Directory?\par
\b0 Ans. What is Delegation in AD?\par
Delegation in Active Directory means giving specific administrative rights to a user or group so they can manage only certain objects (like users, groups, or computers) within an OU, without giving them full domain admin rights.\par
Example: HR team can reset passwords only for HR employees, but not for IT staff.\par
\b Steps to Delegate Administrative Privileges\par
1. Open Active Directory Users and Computers (ADUC)\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b0 Go to Server Manager \u8594? Tools \u8594? Active Directory Users and Computers.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Expand your domain.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 2. Select the Target OU\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj Locate the OU (Organizational Unit) where you want to delegate\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}permissions.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Example: OU = Sales Department.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 3. Start the Delegation Wizard\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj Right-click the OU \u8594? Select Delegate Control.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}This opens the Delegation of Control Wizard.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj\b 4. Choose Users or Groups\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf7\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qj Click Add \u8594? select the user(s) or security group(s) you want to delegate rights to.\par
{\pntext\f7\'B7\tab}Example: Add HR_Admins group.\par
